{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568022"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:08:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:08:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19454"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19454"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.02,0.72,0.02,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12181"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84890"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12181"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19454"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69169"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"107"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"4298"},{"type":"tags","id":"9719"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28816"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28818"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28869"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84890"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of progressive redness, swelling and tenderness of her right ear. She denies any trauma, insect bites, or swimming. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The right pinna and surrounding skin are erythematous, warm, and tender to touch (Image). The external auditory canal appears normal on otoscopy, and the tympanic membrane is intact. There are no vesicles or discharge present.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ramsay Hunt syndrome","Bee sting","Cellulitis","Gout","Otitis externa"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of auricular cellulitis, including erythema, warmth, and tenderness of the pinna and surrounding skin. \u003Cstrong\u003ECellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a bacterial infection of the skin and subcutaneous tissues, typically caused by \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus\u003C/em\u003E species. The progressive nature of symptoms over two days is typical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERamsay Hunt syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by reactivation of varicella-zoster virus in the geniculate ganglion and characteristically presents with facial paralysis and vesicular eruption in the external ear canal or on the pinna. The absence of vesicles and facial weakness makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebee sting\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes immediate pain and swelling at the site, with symptoms peaking within hours. The history would usually be clear, and symptoms would be improving rather than worsening after two days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGout\u003C/strong\u003E can affect the ear cartilage (auricular tophi), but this presents as firm nodules rather than acute inflammation. It is usually chronic and associated with gout elsewhere in the body.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOtitis externa\u003C/strong\u003E is an infection of the external auditory canal that causes pain, particularly with manipulation of the pinna, and often occurs after swimming. The normal appearance of the ear canal on examination makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cellulitis of the ear (auricular cellulitis) presents with erythema, warmth, and tenderness of the pinna and surrounding skin.","Unlike otitis externa, auricular cellulitis involves the skin and soft tissues rather than the ear canal.","The absence of vesicles helps distinguish cellulitis from Ramsay Hunt syndrome."],"references":["Rivera-Morales MD, Rodr\u00edguez-Bel\u00e9n JL, Vera A, Ganti L. Perichondritis: Not All Ear Pain Is Otitis. Cureus. 2020;12(10):e11141. Published 2020 Oct 24. doi:10.7759/cureus.11141"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69169"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19454"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21536"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21536"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/npGjXJ3OyNItKU8JJU7uygBz437yhA.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/npGjXJ3OyNItKU8JJU7uygBz437yhA.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":309,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69169"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-12T19:39:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-12T19:40:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12181"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84890"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups",